{{Infobox language |name=Afshar |states= [[Turkey]], [[Iran]], [[Syria]], [[Afghanistan]] |region= |ethnicity =[[Afshar people]] |speakers= Unknown |ref= |familycolor=Altaic |fam1=[[Turkic languages|Turkic]] |fam2=[[Common Turkic languages|Common Turkic]] |fam3=[[Oghuz languages|Oghuz]] |fam4=Western Oghuz |fam5=[[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]] |fam6=[[South Azerbaijani language|South Azerbaijani]] |script=[[Perso-Arabic script]], [[Latin script]] |iso3=none |iso3comment=(included in {{ethnolink|azb}}) |glotto=afsh1238 |glottorefname=Afshari |notice=IPA }}
'''Afshar''' or '''Afshari''' ({{lang-az|Əfşar türkcəsi}}, افشار تورکجه‌سی, Әфшар түркҹәси; {{lang-tr|Afşar dili or Afşarca}}) is a [[Turkic languages|Turkic language]] spoken in Turkey, [[Iran]], [[Syria]], and parts of [[Afghanistan]] by the [[Afshar people]]. [[Ethnologue]] lists it as a dialect of [[South Azerbaijani language]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Azerbaijani, South|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/azb|website=Ethnologue|accessdate=4 February 2017}}</ref>{{better|date=February 2017}}
Afshar is distinguished by a large number of loanwords from [[Persian language|Persian]] and a rounding of the phoneme {{IPA|/a/}} to {{IPA|[ɒ]}}, as occurred in Uzbek. In many cases, vowels that are rounded in Azerbaijani are not rounded in Afshar. An example of this is {{IPA|/jiz/}} (meaning ''100''), which is {{IPA|/jyz/}} in standard Azerbaijani.
