The labial fricatives are weakly articulated, and have been described as both [[Bilabial consonant|bilabial]] {{IPA|[ɸ, β]}} and [[Labiodental consonant|labiodental]] {{IPA|[f, v]}}. The palatal stops may have some degree of affrication, as {{IPA|[tʃʰ, tʃ]}}<ref name="CA"/>. After nasals or {{IPA|/l/}}, the unaspirated stops become voiced {{IPA|[b, d, ɟ, ɡ, ɢ]}}. Unlike consonant alternation, this occurs also within a morpheme. The Amur dialect deletes some word-final nasals, which leads to voiced stops occurring also word-initially.

Nivkh's [[phoneme|phonemic]] distinction between velar and uvular fricatives ({{IPA|[ɣ]}} vs. {{IPA|[ʁ]}} and {{IPA|[x]}} vs. {{IPA|[χ]}}) is rare among the world’s languages. These sounds do occur in a great deal of languages, but usually they are [[allophone|interchangeable]].

Nivkh features a process of [[lenition|consonant alternation]] not unlike in [[Celtic languages]], in which [[morpheme]]-initial stops alternate with fricatives and trills:<ref name="CA">{{cite journal
|author=Hidetoshi Shiraishi
|year=2000
|title=Nivkh consonant alternation does not involve hardening
