{{Infobox language |name=Southern Oromo |altname=Borana |region=Kenya, Ethiopia |ethnicity=[[Borana Oromo people|Borana Oromo]], [[Sakuye people|Sakuye]] |speakers= {{sigfig|3.95<!--The Ethiopian figure of 3.6M is from Ethn.12 (3.657M), down from 4.734M in Ethn11. Some of the others have been updated since.-->|2}} million |date=no date |ref=e12 |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Cushitic languages|Cushitic]] |fam3=[[Lowland East Cushitic languages|Lowland East]] |fam4=[[Oromoid languages|Oromoid]] |fam5=[[Oromo language|Oromo]] |iso3=gax |glotto=bora1271 |glottorefname=Borana-Arsi-Guji Oromo }}
'''Southern Oromo''', or '''Borana''' (after one of its dialects), is a variety of [[Oromo language|Oromo]] spoken in southern [[Ethiopia]] and northern [[Kenya]] by the [[Borana people]]. Günther Schlee also notes that it is the native language of a number of related peoples, such as the [[Sakuye]].<ref>Schlee, [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1159837 "Interethnic Clan Identities among Cushitic-Speaking Pastoralists", ''Africa''], 55 (1985),p. 21</ref>
Dialects are Borana proper (Boran, Borena), possibly Arsi (Arussi, Arusi) and Guji (Gujji, Jemjem) in Ethiopia and, in [[Kenya]], Karayu, Salale (Selale), Gabra (Gabbra, Gebra) and possibly [[Orma language|Orma]] and [[Waata language|Waata]].
The language is locally and commonly known as ''afaan borana'' ("Borana language").
